x4freetext: About 8 gram of Yb2O3 powder of natural isotopic
composition (>99.99% pure) was pressed at 10 ton/cm2,
and 2.0 cm in diameter. The thickness of samples was
3.320 mm and 3.680 mm. Monitor foils of Nb (99.99%
pure, 0.20 mm thick) and Al (99.999% pure, 0.04 mm
thick) of the same diameter as the pellets were then
attached in front and at the back of each sample.
The relative efficiency is about 68%, and
energy resolution is 1.69 keV at 1332 keV gamma ray
The neutron flux was monitored by a uranium
Irradiation of the samples was lasted about 2
hours with a yield around 3E10 to 4E10 n/(4pi*s). The
groups of samples were wrapped in cadmium foil and
placed at 0deg. and 135deg. angles relative to the
beam direction and centered about the T-Ti target at
An effective deuteron beam energy of 125 keV
and beam current of 200 uA were used to produce
neutrons. The tritium-titanium (T-Ti) target used in
attenuations, self-absorption of the sample, the
neutron fluence fluctuation, the coincidence sum
effect of cascade gamma-rays in the investigated
nuclide and in the counting geometry.
